Proposed upstream change to usbarmory/tamago that would let UEFI consumers
reuse the framework's per-arch CPU packages (arm64, loong64) without
forking.

Status: NOT applied to the cloud-boot working clone, NOT required for the
cloud-boot/tamago-uefi build (which sidesteps the issue by not importing
the framework's per-arch packages at all and reimplementing the small
set of hooks it needs in `uefiboard/board_<arch>.{go,s}`).

This patch is kept here as a design sketch for the eventual upstream PR
that would close the "framework arm64.Init is incompatible with UEFI"
gap noted in cloud-boot/tamago-uefi#README.

Two changes, both gated behind -tags linkhwinit0 so a clean `go build`
(no tags) still produces the upstream bare-metal behavior:

  1. arm64/init.go gets a `//go:build !linkhwinit0` constraint so the
     framework's `arm64.Init` (linkname'd `runtime/goos.Hwinit0`) is
     compiled out when a UEFI board supplies its own Hwinit0.

     Why we need this: under UEFI on AArch64 the firmware has already
     set up the MMU (Normal/Cacheable RAM + Device MMIO mappings) and
     the code/data we run from depends on those mappings. `Init` calls
     `cpu.InitMMU()` which rebuilds EL1 page tables from scratch and
     clobbers the firmware's mappings, hanging bring-up immediately.
     The board's Hwinit0 instead calls `gBS->AllocatePages` to obtain
     a guaranteed-writable heap chunk and wires `goos.RamStart` +
     `goos.Bloc` to it before `osinit` runs.

  2. loong64/init.go gets the same `//go:build !linkhwinit0` constraint
     so the local loong64 framework staging (cloud-boot-local; not in
     upstream yet, cf. usbarmory/tamago#70) doesn't fight a UEFI board
     for ownership of `runtime/goos.Hwinit0`.

Mirrors the existing `!linkcpuinit` and `!linkramstart` pattern; see the
framework's README for the build-tag conventions.

diff --git a/arm64/init.go b/arm64/init.go
index c9c2caf..e5a9810 100644
--- a/arm64/init.go
+++ b/arm64/init.go
@@ -6,6 +6,12 @@
